    fullDescription: 'Pearl is the only gem produced by a living creature, and that difference matters in ways that go beyond the biological. Where every other gemstone is mined — extracted through force from the earth — a pearl is grown. Something irritating enters a mollusc, and the mollusc responds not by fighting or expelling the irritant but by enveloping it, layer by infinitesimal layer, transforming the source of discomfort into something luminous. This is either a metaphor or simply an extraordinary natural process; you can decide which. For June birthdays, pearl has been the primary birthstone since the 1912 standardization by the American National Association of Jewelers, and it carries more accumulated human meaning than perhaps any other gem. In ancient Rome, it was so valuable that Julius Caesar passed legislation restricting who could wear it. In Chinese imperial tradition, it was associated with the Moon and with spiritual wisdom. In Arab tradition, pearls formed from pure dewdrops — the cleaner the drop, the finer the pearl. In Japan, Mikimoto Kōkichi\'s development of the cultured pearl industry in the early 20th century transformed what had been accessible only to the very wealthy into something anyone could wear, while maintaining the fundamental quality that makes pearl extraordinary: it is grown by a living creature, in layers of nacre so thin each one measures half a micrometre, building over years into something that catches light in the distinctive warm way no synthetic material quite replicates. June also has two alternate birthstones — alexandrite, the extraordinary color-change chrysoberyl, and moonstone, with its adularescent blue glow — making June one of the richest birthday months in the gemstone calendar.',
