    fullDescription: 'Peridot is the one gemstone that glows in the dark — or rather, it glows with a warm yellowish-green light that ancient Egyptians believed was the trapped radiance of the sun. They mined it exclusively on the island of Zabargad in the Red Sea, a volcanic island that was a guarded state secret for centuries, and they gave the stones to their pharaohs as symbols of divine power and solar protection. August\'s primary birthstone is also one of the most unusual stones in the gemstone world from a geological standpoint: while most gems form in Earth\'s crust, peridot forms in the mantle — the layer below the crust that sits above the outer core. It is brought to the surface by volcanic eruptions, which is why it is commonly found in volcanic rocks, why Hawaiian beaches contain tiny grains of it, and why the ancient story of peridot as the tears of Pele (the Hawaiian volcano goddess) has a literal geological truth embedded in the mythology. More extraordinary still: peridot has been found in meteorites. The pallasite class of iron-nickel meteorites — some of the most visually striking meteorites in existence — contains olivine crystals (the mineral of which peridot is the gem quality version) that formed in the cores of planetesimals, small planetary bodies that broke apart in the early solar system. The peridot in some pallasites is billions of years old and formed not on Earth but in space. August has two additional birthstones — spinel (added to the official list in 2016) and sardonyx — making it a month of options. But peridot, with its volcanic origin, its extraterrestrial connections, and its five-thousand-year history as the sun\'s gemstone, is the one that tells the most interesting story.',
