    history: 'Opal has been mined in Europe for at least 2,000 years, with ancient deposits in what is now Slovakia supplying most of the ancient world. The Romans prized opal above almost all other stones — Pliny the Elder wrote that opal combined the beauty of every other gem: "the red fire of the carbuncle, the purple of the amethyst, the sea-green of the emerald, dazzling and glittering in a remarkable way" [Pliny the Elder, c. 77 CE, Naturalis Historia]. The discovery of Australian opal deposits in the 1870s–1900s, particularly at Coober Pedy, White Cliffs, and Lightning Ridge, gave the world an entirely new scale of supply. [American Gem Society, ags.org]',
