    fullDescription: 'Opal is the stone that contains all the other stones. Pliny the Elder understood this in 77 CE and said so directly: opal combines the red of ruby, the green of emerald, the blue of sapphire, the purple of amethyst — "dazzling and glittering in a remarkable way." For a stone that lacks any crystal structure and is technically a mineraloid rather than a mineral, opal has generated more poetry, more mythology, and more passionate devotion than almost any other gem. The play of color — the technical term for the shifting spectral fire that moves across the surface of fine opal as you tilt it — is caused by diffraction of light through billions of silica spheres, arranged in near-perfect order, like a naturally occurring diffraction grating at the nanometre scale. The same physics that makes soap bubbles iridescent makes opal ignite with color. Australia produces roughly 95% of the world\'s precious opal, a result of a specific geological history: the inland sea that once covered much of central Australia left behind silica-rich sediments that later formed opals as ground water slowly deposited them in cracks and voids in the rock. The Lightning Ridge fields in New South Wales produce the rare and extraordinarily valuable black opal — dark body color that makes the play of color, particularly reds and oranges, appear even more intense, like fire viewed against a dark sky. The story of opal\'s bad luck reputation is instructive: entirely invented by Sir Walter Scott in an 1829 novel, it was believed within years by people who had never read the novel. A gem this beautiful probably required a cautionary legend — humans distrust what seems too perfect.',
